“Democracy’s sometimes messy,” said Joe Biden, who urged calm. Later, in a stunning news conference, President Trump lied and conjured up a conspiracy.
Even “Fox & Friends,” a warm venue for President Trump, sounded doubts about his talk of a stolen election.
The major networks cut away as the president lobbed false claims.
Protests have broken out all year long across America, and they are not letting up now.
The count goes on, but we appear to be closer to a winner.
Other outlets feel they’re sure, but we’re not certain enough about the votes that remain to be counted.
Joe Biden received one of his highest margins in California, but a look at how the state’s ballot measures were decided reflects a complex electorate.
During an emotional conference call, Democrats traded excuses, blame and prognostications about how their expectations for big gains went so wrong.
New York’s governor found a familiar scapegoat for Democrats’ election losses: New York City’s mayor.
The president’s victory in his adopted home state has Democrats once again worrying about their future electoral prospects.
In its short life span, it was one of the fastest growing groups in Facebook’s history and a hub for those trying to delegitimize the election.
Facebook, alarmed by election misinformation, is said to be implementing new measures to slow its spread.
On Election Day, Facebook and Twitter did better by making their products worse, our columnist writes.
